<h4>Step 1:</h4> Flow solder onto the two positive pads on the edge of the battery holder outline and a small amount onto the central negative pad. <p> <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/BPkF7ItYe9k" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> <p> [[Continue|Step 2]] [[I need help|Step 1 - Troubleshooting]] [[Back to the homepage|OTIS Assembly Guide]]<h4>Step 1 - Troubleshooting</h4> <ul> <li>If solder won't flow check your iron tip is free from any black oxidation and it has been tinned with solder.</li> <li>If any copper is showing through the iron plating the tip has worn down and needs to be replaced.</li> <li>Check your iron temperature is set to 370°C for lead based solder or 390°C for lead-free solder.</li> <li>Check the solder you are using has a flux core and is ideally lead based.</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 1|Step 1]] [[Continue to Step 2|Step 2]]<h4>Step 2:</h4> Place the battery holder in its location on the board and use tweezers to apply pressure to the top of it. <p> [[Continue|Step 3]] [[Back|Step 1]] [[I need help|Step 2 - Troubleshooting]]<h4>Step 3:</h4> Reflow the solder on the pads, making sure the pads of the holder are flat on the surface of the board. <p> [[If you have a board that does not have resistors presoldered click here to complete some additional steps|Step 3 (Offshoot)]] [[Continue|Step 4]] [[Back|Step 2]] [[I need help|Step 3 - Troubleshooting]]<h4>Step 2 - Troubleshooting</h4> <ul> <li>Don't apply enough pressure to bend the metal, just enough to firmly clamp the holder to the board.</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 2|Step 2]] [[Continue to Step 3|Step 3]]<h4>Step 4:</h4> Insert the switch into the holes on the right side of the board, with the black slider facing outwards. bent back into shape or replaced.</li> <li>Check that there is a CR2032's worth of height and a bit more to account for the spring from the board to the back of the battery holder.</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 3|Step 3]] [[Continue to Step 4|Step 4]]<h4>Step 5:</h4> Insert the LED pins through the holes with the longest pin facing towards the switch. <p> <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/PktxJEJBNFY" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> <p> [[Continue|Step 6]] [[Back|Step 4]] [[I need help|Step 5 - Troubleshooting]]<h4>Step 4 - Troubleshooting</h4> <ul> <li>Make sure you insert the switch so the metal casing is on the top side of the board, with the image.</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 4|Step 4]] [[Continue to Step 5|Step 5]]<h4>Step 6:</h4> Flip the board over and solder the parts in place, making sure the parts are flush with the board and there alt="Image of LED flat edge"></img><p> <li>Do not force the LEDs into the holes, if they will not go in you either have them oriented wrong or there is solder left over from kit manufacturing stuck in the holes which will need to be removed.</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 5|Step 5]] [[Continue to Step 6|Step 6]]<h4>Step 7:</h4> Push the badge pin through the hole in the centre of the board and hold it in place with the clasp on the other side. <p> [[Continue|Step 8]] [[Back|Step 6]] <h4>Step 6 - Troubleshooting</h4> <ul> <li>The spacing between the pins on the LEDs is very small (this will be fixed in a future board revision) be careful not to short two pads together.</li> <li>If you do short two pads use solder wick to remove the solder and start over.</li> <li>If the solder joints look crusty or have holes in them then you will need to use solder wick and retry.</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 6|Step 6]] [[Continue to Step 7|Step 7]]<h4>Step 8:</h4> Decide what colours you want your LEDs to show what colour it controls. Flow solder to close the connection for each colour you would like to be lit. <p> <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/PktxJEJBNFY" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> <p> [[Continue|Step 10]] [[Back|Step 8]] [[I need help|Step 9 - Troubleshooting]]<h4>Step 10:</h4> If you are not shorting the blue jumper on the LED next to the badge pin stick the included piece of tape over the pad to avoid the clasp connecting it (this is an error in the prototype design). <p> [[Continue|Step 11]] [[Back|Step 9]]<h4>Step 9 - Troubleshooting</h4> <ul> <li>If you flow solder into a connection and want to disconnect it, use solder wick to remove the solder.</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 9|Step 9]] [[Continue to Step 10|Step 10]]<h4>Step 11:</h4> Remove the CR2032 coin cell from its packaging and insert it into the battery holder. <p> [[Continue|Step 12]] [[Back|Step 10]] [[I need help|Step 11 - Troubleshooting]]<h4>Step 12:</h4> Flick the switch and verify the LEDs light as intended. <p> <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/8DNA1CCd7PA" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> <p> [[Back|Step 11]] [[Done - back to the homepage|OTIS Assembly Guide]] [[It doesn't work...|Step 12 - Troubleshooting]] <h4>Step 11 - Troubleshooting</h4> <ul> <li>If the battery does not seem to be making good contact you may need to flow more solder into the negative pad to add more tension or remove and adjust the placement of the battery holder.</li> <li>To remove the battery holder heat up both pads while applying upwards force with tweezers (remove the battery first).</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 11|Step 11]] [[Continue to Step 12|Step 12]]<h4>Step 12 - Troubleshooting</h4> <ul> <li>Make sure all parts have no holes or black spots in the solder joints (if necessary flow more solder in).</li> <li>Try applying pressure to the battery holder, if the LEDs light there is a poor connection between the battery and the board, make sure the pins of the battery holder are flush with the board and the two clips on the top of the holder are touching the battery. Adding more solder to the negative pad may also fix this problem.</li> <li>If you soldered your own resistors, this is most likely the cause of your problem, go back to [[the Step 3 (Offshoot) troubleshooting page|Step 3 (Offshoot) - Troubleshooting]] and follow the steps there.</li> <li>There are some images of what a fully assembled kit should look like below.</li> <img src=" [[Back to the homepage|OTIS Assembly Guide]]<h4>Welcome to the website for Project OTIS, the Leeds Raspberry Jam (<a href="https://twitter.com/LeedsRaspJam">twitter</a>) owl badge.</h4> OTIS (out there initiating STEM) is designed to be an easy to assemble and customisable beginner's soldering kit, featuring a metallic owl design on the front, 4 RGB LEDS (can be set to one of seven colours individually) and is powered by a CR2032 battery. <img src=" Information|Credits & Licensing Information]] [[View the feedback form|Feedback Form]]<h4>Diagrams</h4> Note - these files may or may not be complete and are not guaranteed to be in a usable state. Please check before using them and follow the restrictions detailed on the [[licensing page|Credits & Licensing Information]]. <a href="files/M3.brd">EAGLE Board File</a> <a href="files/M3.sch">EAGLE Schematic</a> <a href="files/M3-Gerbers.zip">Gerbers</a> <a href="files/Owl Images.zip">Owl Images</a> [[Back to the homepage|OTIS Assembly Guide]]<h4>GitHub:</h4> <a href="https://github.com/leedsraspjam/OTIS">View this website's source code on GitHub.</a> <p> [[Back to the homepage|OTIS Assembly Guide]]<h4>Step 3 (Offshoot):</h4> Welcome to the unsoldered kit specific section. There should be six strips of resistors. Three will be longer than the others - put them to one side, they are spares and you shouldn't need them unless you make a mistake. You should now have three strips of between one and two resistors. There is *very* small lettering on all of them showing the value. You may need a microscope or other optical enlargement device to read them. Conversion Table: Marking - Location - Value 470 - R2, R3 - 47 ohm 121 - R1 - 120 ohm 0 - R4, R5 - 0 ohm link (Note - you may have a different preffered way of soldering resistors than the one described below, TL;DR just solder the resistor values shown above to the locations also above.) If you can, switch to a fine pitch conical tip now, it will make the soldering ahead much easier. Flow solder onto just one of the pads for all the part locations detailed above (each location is labelled with both the value of resistor to be placed there and it's identifier in white lettering on the board.) Follow these steps for all three strips. First, remove the plastic cover from the top of the strip, use tweezers if you cannot do it by hand. Being careful not to accidentally inhale the resistors, pick one up with tweezers and place it on the board location shown in the table above. Hold it in place and reflow the side you have already soldered. After making sure the part is securely in place, continue to solder the other side in place. If necessary, touch up the side you soldered originally and ensure both pads have a nice smooth, shiny joint. If you make a mistake soldering a resistor (and you most likely will) or simply lose one, I've included three spare strips. If necessary, you can desolder a resistor by applying upwards pressure with tweezers while simultaneously heating both sides. <p> <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/K_Zzi4qLBEw" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> <p> [[Go back to Step 3|Step 3]] [[I need help|Step 3 (Offshoot) - Troubleshooting]]<h4>Step 3 (Offshoot) - Troubleshooting</h4> <ul> <li>If you have any, apply flux to all pads before soldering. This will clean off oxides that have formed since the boards were manufactured.</li> <li>Avoid lead-free solder, both in general for hand soldering and especially so for SMD soldering. Use a high quality 60/40 solder with a rosin flux core for best results.</li> <li>If you have issues later on, the resistors are most likely the culprit, if a specific colour on an LED doesn't work or some LEDs don't work altogether reflow all the joints on your resistors and make sure they are flush with the board.</li> </ul> [[Back to Step 3 (Offshoot)|Step 3 (Offshoot)]] <h4>Feedback Form:</h4> The feedback form is available at the link below: <a href="https://otis.leedsraspjam.co.uk/feedback">https://otis.leedsraspjam.co.uk/feedback</a> [[Back to the homepage|OTIS Assembly Guide]]
